Here is the design for The Singing Sea Puzzle.

ENCOUNTER: THE RESONANCE FIELD
Location: The Sea of Ghosts, North of the College.
Goal: Cross the frictionless ice field to reach the Singing Glacier.
The Hazard: The water is lethal (Hypothermia). The ice is frictionless (Newtonian movement).
I. THE MECHANICS (The Physics of the Puzzle)
The field is a grid of dark, freezing water interspersed with Static Obstacles (Rocks, Shipwrecks, Glaciers) and Mobile Platforms (Ice Floes).
Rule 1: The Slide (Jumping On)
When a character jumps onto an Ice Floe from a static point:
The Floe moves in the direction of the jump.
It does not stop until it hits a Static Obstacle, another Floe, or the edge of the map.
Example: Kyboh jumps North onto a Floe. The Floe slides North until it hits a rock.
Rule 2: The Kickback (Jumping Off)
When a character jumps off a Floe:
The character lands in the target square.
The Floe is pushed in the opposite direction (NewtonΓÇÖs Third Law).
Example: Saijah jumps West off the Floe to a rock. The Floe slides East until it hits something.
Rule 3: Mass & Inertia
Small Floes (1x1): Can carry 1 person. Move fast.
Large Floes (2x2): Can carry the whole party. Require a Combined Might Check (or Kyboh) to get moving from a standstill, but once moving, they smash through smaller obstacles (Breakable Ice).
The Environmental Hazard: The Water
If a Floe slides off the map or a player misses a jump: They fall in.
Effect: 4 Cold Damage immediately. Requires a Might Check to climb back onto the nearest solid object. If they fail, they begin drowning/freezing.

II. THE MAP LAYOUT (The 3 Stages)
Stage 1: The Tutorial (The Straight Shot)
A simple setup to teach the rules.
Setup: One Small Floe. A straight line of water. A rock wall at the end.
Solution: Jump on (Slide North). Hit Wall. Jump Off.
The Lesson: "It doesn't stop until it hits something."
Stage 2: The Ricochet (The Angle)
The path to the next checkpoint is blocked by a massive jagged iceberg. They cannot go straight.
Setup: A Large Floe. Obstacles arranged in a staggered pattern (Rocks to the East and West).
The Puzzle:
Jump East onto the Floe. (It hits the East Rock).
Jump North off the Floe? No, that pushes the Floe South.
Solution: The party must realize they need to hit the rocks in a specific order to "bank" the floe around the central obstacle. Or, one person jumps off to kick the floe in a new direction while the others stay on.


Stage 3: The Ferryman (The Split Party)
The final stretch is a massive open expanse of water. There is only one Large Floe (The Ferry).
The Problem: The "Kickback" rule. To move the Ferry forward, someone has to jump backward off it to propel it.
The Solution:
The party gets on the Ferry.
One member (The Sacrifice) jumps South back to the starting rock.
The Ferry shoots North with the rest of the party.
The Rescue: Now the party is at the destination, but one member is left behind. They must use the Small Floes scattered around the perimeter to build a bridge or send a retrieval vehicle back for them.



III. CHARACTER UTILITY (Breaking the Puzzle)
The players can use their specific abilities to manipulate the puzzle, rewarding creativity.
1. Kyboh: The Human Engine
The Gloves: His gloves resonate with the ice. He doesn't need to jump to move a floe. He can punch the air (or the ice) to create a Kinetic Pulse.
Utility: He can stand on a floe and punch South to drive the floe North, acting as an outboard motor.
The Risk: Every time he does this, roll a d20. On a 1, his gloves overload and crack the ice beneath him, turning a Large Floe into a Small one (or sinking a Small one).
2. Alfonso: The Anchor
The Ghoul: Alfonso can summon/use his Ghoul to act as "The Sacrifice."
Utility: He orders the Ghoul to jump off the floe to propel the party forward, leaving the ghoul behind to drown/freeze.
The Vibe: Ruthless efficiency. Ylva loves it.
3. Davinia: The Ice Shaper
The Crown: Her magic is now Ice-as-Structure.
Utility: She can cast a spell to create a Temporary Obstacle (Ice Wall) in the water. This allows the party to create "brakes" or "banking points" where there were none.
The Cost: This counts as casting a spell (FP cost).
4. Saijah: The Scout
Mobility: She has the best Agility. She can leap between moving floes.
Utility: She can jump ahead to a distant rock, catch a sliding floe with a rope, and tie it off to stop it safely.

IV. THE THREAT: THE CHILDREN OF THE COLD
ItΓÇÖs not just a puzzle; itΓÇÖs a combat encounter.
Enemies: Ice Wraiths (TL 1 Skirmishers).
Behavior: They hover. They ignore the friction rules. They swarm the party while they are trapped on the moving ice.
